title: For Sale:  Widow Maker - Winchester Md 11
postcontent:
The infamous WIDOW MAKER, Winchester Md 11, SL 12 ga semi-auto.  Not an uncommon piece, but it is uncommon being fully functional and in this good of condition.

This John Brown design was so named the WIDOW MAKER as there was no operating lever on the bolt.  To chamber a round, the operator had to place the butt on a flat surface.  Then a knurdled portion of the barrel is gripped to push the barrel down into the shotgun about four inches and released, usually with the muzzle pointed at the opertor's head.  What amazes me the most, by 1912 Winchester recognized the design flaw and would give a new Model 12 to each person who turned in the 11, but continued to sell the 11 until 1925.

Asking price for this odd ball is $350.

title: For Sale:  Midwest Industries SS Free Float Tube
postcontent: Midwest Industries SS-Series Free Float Tube Handguard system, it measuring around 12 1/2 inches long. This is used but in good condition with only a few minor scuffs and scrapes. I have given it a complete cleaning (all threaded parts thread and turn freely by hand). You will need RED lock tight NOT blue. If you use blue lock tight I suspect that the barren nut with be damaged should you decide to remove the free float tube at a later date. And remember when using any lock tight "a dab will do". It is important for me to note that there was a small locking nut on the bottom of the free float tube that I striped out the first time I tried to install it. The purpose of this locking nut is to ensure a positive lock between the free float tube and the barrel nut. I never used it and with the little bit of RED lock tight that came with the system I have had zero problems.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Leupold HAMR, Ballistic Plates, Eagle Plate Carrier
postcontent:
First up for sale or trade is a Leupold Mark 4 4x24.  You can see it mounted here:

http://a1.sphotos.ak.fbcdn.net/hphotos-ak-ash4/431193_REDACTED94_193308475_37177460_317882615_n.jpg

Actually, it is the Leupold HAMR without the reflex sight on top.  A red dot can still be mounted.  I was thinking about putting a Trijicon RMR on it, but never got around to it.  As far as the details of this scope, this is pretty much Leupold's answer to the ACOG.  It is a fixed power 4x magnification with illuminated horse shoe with 1 MOA dot (uses batteries, but etched glass means you can still see it when it is off unlike aimpoints and eotechs) and an unlit BDC.  The glass is extremely clear, and the ocular lense (the one you look into) is HUGE compared to ACOG's.  Great field of view and more eye relief than an ACOG making it easier and faster to get sight pucture.  It is also very streamlined.  It looks great and functions even better.  Sadly though it has only ever been mounted and sighted in.  Still essentially brand new.  The picatinny mount comes off so that it can mount on a carry handle.  Comes in original box with all papers, including the warranty card for you to turn in.  New these go for about $1350 but since it is technically used, I am looking at $1150 OBO.

I have one set of level IV stand alone ceramic plates.  They are both triple curve with the front being shooter's cut and the back recantgular.  They weigh 7.5 and 8 lbs respectively.  They will stop an armor piercing 30-06 round.  In brand new condition, pictured on left, asking $400 OBO.

I have another set of level III stand alone polyethylene/ceramic composite plates.  They are both single curve with shooter's cut.  They weigh 3.5 lbs each and are pretty much identical.  At level III they will stop a .308, but when used with IIIA soft armor they make a level IV system.  They show some wear from the vest rubbing against them (pictured on right), but no cracks, chips, etc.  Nice thing about these is while they haven't been dropped, doing so will not cause them to crack or shatter like ceramic.  Can be found online for about $600 a set, I'm asking $450 OBO.

Last is an Eagle Industries Universal Tactical Vest.  This vest is designed to take the non-standard sized body armor that many law enforcement use.  It has a system of straps and velcro to properly position the kevlar panels for maximum protection and comfort.  It also holds standard SAPI plates with a top opening velcro closure for easy installation and removal of ballistic plates.  This means if you happen to have some heavy ceramics, you can leave them out for low risk stuff where you need speed more than protection like foot pursuits, and then drop them in for the high risk stuff like active shooters and barricaded gunmen where greater protection is desired.  Vest is in "like new" condition, no rips, tears, cuts, abrasions, stains, smells, or even dirt.  Does not come with patches or any ballistic protection.  Sells for $200 on Eagle's site, asking $150 OBO.

Now the part where I tell you not to send me stupid offers.  If you do I may respond, but it will only be to make fun of you.  However, if you do have something cheaper but are willing to pay the difference, that is fine.  I will ship to anywhere in the lower 48, but you pay shipping.  If you trade a firearm, we pay each others shipping, and I cover my transfer fees on this end (seems obvious, but just making sure).  If you want more information or pictures feel free to e-mail me with questions.  You can also call or text me at (4O2) 6l2-eight nine two nine

postcontent:
I have a Springfield XDm 5.25 chambered in .45ACP, with a PRP Trigger Kit installed and a Patriot Magwell, that I would like to trade.  

From the Powder River Precision website about the trigger kit (plus I am including the stock trigger):
"This Drop in Trigger Kit fits all XDM pistols including the new XDM5.25". The kit contains our famous striker safety lever, to remove the long trigger pre-travel on the XDM trigger. Reduced power: trigger spring, sear spring, striker safety spring and striker spring, to lower the pull weight. Our trigger is made of tough light weight polymer that helps speed up the reset. It also has an integral over travel stop on the back of the trigger. Using this method of over travel stop removes added stress on the trigger bar that are present with any of the other over travel stop methods. This trigger is a Springfield Armory OEM part available on production XD and XDM pistols from the factory (see APPENDIX D4 â€” 21.6 Production Division Rules). When installed correctly, the kit will give you a short crisp trigger pull (about 3.5-4.5lbs) with a fast reset and shorten the total trigger pull length. Fits all XDMs."  [url]http://shop.powderriverprecision.net/product.sc?productId=73&categoryId=3[/url]

Tweaking our design for the benefit of an affective product that will fit the IDPA box, this magwell will make your ESP machine rock! These daggers were very dangerous for German to sell after WWII as anything Nazi was deemed illegal for Germans and punished harshly in Post War Germany.  I am asking $300 ea. OBO. Please call REDACTED.
